  abstract = {In northern Canada, shallow-lake-rich freshwater landscapes provide key habitat for many wildlife species and play a vital role in the traditional use of the land by local indigenous communities. Changes in precipitation have the potential to substantially alter the hydrological conditions of these shallow lakes. Here we compare multiple years of measurements of lake water oxygen isotope composition ({$\delta$}18Omes) with surface sediment cellulose-inferred lake water oxygen isotope composition ({$\delta$}18Oinf) for \textasciitilde{}80 lakes in two of Canada's largest lake-rich thermokarst landscapes \textendash{} Old Crow Flats (OCF), Yukon, and western Hudson Bay Lowlands (HBL), Manitoba. Results reveal a strikingly coherent pattern of recent hydrological change in these two landscapes. In OCF, {$\delta$}18Oinf values from snowmelt-dominated lakes align reasonably well with the 2007-2008 {$\delta$}18Omes values from the early ice-free season, as expected. In contrast, {$\delta$}18Oinf from rainfall-dominated lakes are systematically lower (i.e., more 18O-depleted) relative to {$\delta$}18Omes. Climate data indicate that the winter of 2007-08 had markedly lower snowfall compared to the long-term mean, whereas winters immediately prior to our water sample collections were characterized by snowfall equal to or greater than the long-term mean. Thus, we speculate that the isotopic offset between {$\delta$}18Oinf and {$\delta$}18Omes for some of the lakes is due to a shift to more rainfall-dominated precipitation. Similar results have been obtained from lakes in HBL. Here too, about 40\% of the sampled lakes contain {$\delta$}18Oinf values that are lower than {$\delta$}18Omes values from 2010-2012, which may also reflect a recent shift to more rainfall-dominated precipitation. These findings suggest that some lakes in our study areas received less snowmelt during the water sampling years in comparison to the time interval captured in the surface-sediments. Notably, a few lakes in HBL lost all of their water to evaporation during mid-summer 2010, fuelling concerns that reduction in snowmelt and an increase in the length of the ice-free season in these landscapes may lead to an increase in the occurrence of lake desiccation.},
  language = {English},
